summaries.title: Representation and Visibility in Engineering Spaces
summaries.summaryText: She emphasized how few Black women were visible in faculty and leadership roles, describing representation as both motivating and emotionally taxing. Her NSBE involvement offered vital affirmation and a platform to advocate for equity. [Part 4/4]

summaries.title: Balancing Academic Rigor with Limited Peer Representation
summaries.summaryText: Maria described feeling academically capable but often isolated in her computer engineering courses, where few other Latina students were enrolled. She mentioned that faculty were supportive when approached, but that representation and group belonging remained low, especially during first-year lab sections. [Part 3/4]

summaries.title: Building Inclusive Engineering Teams
summaries.summaryText: Ethan noted that successful project outcomes often came from teams with diverse backgrounds and perspectives. He believes empathy and active listening should be core engineering competencies. [Part 4/4]

summaries.title: Transition from High School to University-Level Engineering
summaries.summaryText: Luis found the shift from project-based high school learning to theory-heavy coursework challenging but rewarding. [Part 3/4]

summaries.title: Navigating Gender Bias in Research Environments
summaries.summaryText: She recounted experiences where her technical contributions were overlooked and strategies she used to assert confidence. [Part 2/4]

summaries.title: Integrating Mental Health Advocacy with STEM Identity
summaries.summaryText: Sarah described bridging mental health awareness into STEM culture through peer-led workshops. [Part 1/4]

themes.title: Cultural Representation as a Source of Motivation
themes.description: Seeing Latino professionals at SHPE events reinforced Maria’s sense of purpose and belonging in a field where representation remains limited. [Extended 1]

themes.title: Team Diversity as an Engineering Strength
themes.description: Ethan believes interdisciplinary and culturally diverse teams drive better innovation outcomes, reflecting the growing importance of social awareness in engineering practice. [Extended 2]

themes.title: Peer Mentorship as a Belonging Intervention
themes.description: Daniel emphasized how structured mentorship programs provided psychological safety and belonging cues, normalizing struggle and improving persistence among marginalized students. [Extended 4]

themes.title: Navigating Institutional Barriers as a First-Generation Student
themes.description: First-generation identity shapes how Maria interprets bureaucratic and academic systems, creating additional cognitive and emotional labor compared to continuing-generation peers. [Extended 4]

themes.title: Navigating Institutional Barriers as a First-Generation Student
themes.description: First-generation identity shapes how Maria interprets bureaucratic and academic systems, creating additional cognitive and emotional labor compared to continuing-generation peers. [Extended 3]

themes.title: Acknowledging Structural Advantage and Allyship in STEM
themes.description: Ethan’s reflections underscore the role of allyship among students who recognize their positional privilege. He highlights how acknowledging systemic inequities can lead to more equitable classroom dynamics. [Extended 3]

themes.title: Sense of Belonging in STEM for Students of Color
themes.description: Maria’s reflections highlight how peer representation and visibility in classrooms significantly influence belonging and persistence for Latina women in engineering. [Extended 1]

themes.title: First-Generation Adaptation to STEM Rigor
themes.description: Luis’s story demonstrates resilience through peer and cultural support. [Extended 3]

quotes.quoteText: It took me a year to realize struggling is normal — not a sign that I’m not supposed to be here. [Context 4]
quotes.context: Daniel describing the turning point after joining peer mentoring programs.

quotes.quoteText: My parents don’t really understand what I study, but they tell everyone I’m going to be an engineer — that means a lot, but it’s also scary. [Context 3]
quotes.context: Daniel reflecting on parental expectations and emotional weight of being first-gen.

quotes.quoteText: Sometimes I feel like everyone else just gets it — like I’m pretending to belong in these classes. [Context 3]
quotes.context: Daniel discussing his sense of imposter syndrome in engineering coursework.

quotes.quoteText: I love leading projects, but it’s exhausting always being the one to explain why diversity matters in engineering teams. [Context 3]
quotes.context: Aaliyah describing the advocacy work tied to her leadership role.

quotes.quoteText: I wish there were a clearer path for first-gen students to find mentorship — it feels like everyone else already knows the rules. [Context 3]
quotes.context: Maria discussing gaps in support infrastructure.

quotes.quoteText: My parents always say 'you represent the family'—it motivates me but also adds pressure. [Context 3]
quotes.context: Priya describing family expectations.

quotes.quoteText: I love leading projects, but it’s exhausting always being the one to explain why diversity matters in engineering teams. [Context 4]
quotes.context: Aaliyah describing the advocacy work tied to her leadership role.

quotes.quoteText: Seeing other Latina engineers at the SHPE conference made me feel like I’m not alone — like I really do belong in this field. [Context 3]
quotes.context: Maria reflecting on peer support and cultural representation.

quotes.quoteText: When I walk into a classroom and see no one who looks like me, I remind myself that my presence opens the door for someone else. [Context 3]
quotes.context: Aaliyah reflecting on the impact of representation and visibility.

quotes.quoteText: Sometimes I look around my class and I’m the only Latina — it makes me question whether I belong here. [Context 3]
quotes.context: Maria reflecting on classroom representation and belonging.

quotes.quoteText: No one in my family went to college, so I didn’t even know how office hours worked my first semester. [Context 3]
quotes.context: Maria describing her initial confusion with academic expectations as a first-gen student.

quotes.quoteText: You can’t innovate if you’re burned out — STEM needs to start treating wellness as part of success. [Context 3]

areasForImprovement.title: Formal Recognition for Student Advocacy and Mentorship Work
areasForImprovement.description: Students like Aaliyah contribute substantial unpaid labor in mentoring and advocacy roles. Institutions should recognize these contributions as part of leadership and service learning frameworks. [Extended 2]
actionItems: Create service-learning credit for mentorship and advocacy roles
Include advocacy experience in leadership award criteria

areasForImprovement.title: Increase Cultural Representation in Engineering Programs
areasForImprovement.description: Students emphasized the importance of seeing role models and mentors from similar cultural backgrounds. Faculty partnerships with student cultural organizations could foster inclusion and belonging. [Extended 3]
actionItems: Integrate cultural competence into departmental events

areasForImprovement.title: Broaden Access to Early Engineering Exposure Programs
areasForImprovement.description: Ethan’s reflection highlights unequal early access to STEM exposure. Partnering with local schools and community programs can help level the playing field for underrepresented groups. [Extended 3]
actionItems: Create summer bridge programs for high school students
Offer needs-based scholarships for pre-college engineering camps

areasForImprovement.title: Expand Visibility of First-Gen Student Resources
areasForImprovement.description: Current communication about financial aid, academic advising, and mentorship resources does not adequately reach first-generation students. Improving targeted outreach through orientation and department emails could reduce inequities in access to support. [Extended 1]
actionItems: Add first-gen resource links to department portals
